<a id="a6a00d8341c4eab53ef0148c67127ce970c"></a>


<h3>Kaye: <em> The Regulation of Corporate Tax Shelters in the U.S.</em></h3>


<a href="http://law.shu.edu/Faculty/fulltime_faculty/Tracy-Kaye.cfm" target="_blank">Tracy A. Kaye</a> (Seton Hall) has published <a href="http://comparativelaw.metapress.com/content/h63n51567j036028/" target="_blank">The Regulation of Corporate Tax Shelters in the United States</a>, 58 Am. J. Comp. L. 585 (2010). Here is the <a href="http://comparativelaw.metapress.com/content/h63n51567j036028/" target="_blank">abstract</a>:
<blockquote>
<p>No other topic in the tax realm has sparked more controversy and commentary than the subject of corporate tax shelters. Even with decades of legislation specifically focused on shutting down corporate tax shelters, some tax advisors continue to create ingenious plans to exploit any inconsistencies in the tax laws. This Article describes the judiciary's involvement in the determination of unacceptable tax avoidance through its development of such common law doctrines as "substance-over-form," "step transaction," "business purpose," and "economic substance." Focusing on the last decade, it surveys the array of penalties, disclosure requirements, and substantive changes to the Code that are intended to curb the use of tax shelters and discusses the executive branch's initiatives that have been issued in the form of notices, revenue rulings, and Treasury regulations. The large current and projected federal budget deficits have generated much legislative and executive branch interest in raising revenue by closing "tax loopholes" or reducing the tax gap through further restrictions on tax shelters. The Article concludes by exploring the Obama Administration's proposal and the codification of the economic substance doctrine that was included in the health care legislation.</p>
</blockquote>



